t Effect: -0.01586350220254379\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["SNAP days show a clear increase in demand, with average sales rising from approximately 3.16 to 3.34 units. This pattern holds even after controlling for price and baseline demand, where the regression estimates a positive SNAP effect of about +0.052. This suggests that SNAP benefits act as a meaningful driver of purchasing behavior, likely by increasing consumers’ effective buying power.\n","\n","In contrast, event days do not show a meaningful impact on demand. Average sales remain nearly unchanged between event and non-event periods, and the regression coefficient is slightly negative (-0.016). This indicates that events do not generate incremental demand and may instead reflect shifts in purchase timing rather than true increases in overall consumption.\n","\n","Overall, SNAP appears to be a consistent and material demand driver, while event signals contribute little to overall sales volume."],"metadata":{"id":"J0wEFp3zGvBs"},"id":"J0wEFp3zGvBs"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Final Comparison\n"],"metadata":{"id":"0JZBuKVdQaAi"},"id":"0JZBuKVdQaAi"},{"cell_type":"code","source":["print(\"\\n===== MODEL COMPARISON =====\")\n","print(f\"Baseline RMSE: {rmse_base:.2f} | MAE: {mae_base:.2f} | R²: {r2_base:.2f}\")\n","print(f\"Regression RMSE: {rmse_reg:.2f} | MAE: {mae_reg:.2f} | R²: {r2_reg:.2f}\")\n","print(f\"Elasticity: {elasticity:.3f}\")"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"zxyTyIgaQc7d","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1776810570411,"user_tz":300,"elapsed":3,"user":{"displayName":"Panav Ladha","userId":"05161850510770886297"}},"outputId":"dcb758a7-95a2-40b6-b9f8-45150a9ab5b3"},"id":"zxyTyIgaQc7d","execution_count":23,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["\n","===== MODEL COMPARISON =====\n","Baseline RMSE: 2.18 | MAE: 0.99 | R²: 0.63\n","Regression RMSE: 3.42 | MAE: 1.49 | R²: 0.53\n","Elasticity: -0.046\n"]}]},{"cell_typ